                {
                    "name": "Notes",
                    "url": "",
                    "facts": "",
                    "issue": "",
                    "ruling": "",
                    "significance": "",
                    "correlation": "",
                    "details": "",
                    "enum1": "1. The death of a party does not excuse non-performance of a contract which involves property rights.",
                    "enum2": "2. It is only after the debts are paid that the residue of the estate is distributed among the successors.",
                    "enum3": "3. Heir’s liability shall only be limited up to the value of the property they received from the decedent.",
                    "enum4": "4. The  inheritance  vests  immediately  upon  the decedent’s  death without a moment of interruption, and NOT at the time the heirs are declared as such, nor at the time of partition, nor at the distribution of properties.",
                    "enum5": "5. The capacity of the heir is determined as of the time the decedent died.",
                    "enum6": "7. The right is always deemed to retroact to the moment of death of the decedent.",
                    "enum7": "",
                    "enum8": "",
                    "children": [
                        {
                            "name": "Co-Ownership",
                            "url": "",
                            "facts": "",
                            "issue": "",
                            "ruling": "",
                            "significance": "",
                            "correlation": "",
                            "details": "",
                            "enum1": "6. At the precise moment of death, heirs become owners pro-indiviso. They become absolute owners of their undivided aliquots share but with respect to the individual properties, they become co-owners. This co-ownership remains until partition. Until then, individual heirs cannot claim any rights over a specific property. There is a need for partition before title to a particular property vest in the heirs. However, legatees, and devisees bequeathed specific properties do not require court adjudication; the testator himself had already identified these.",
